    "best_read": "Catch in shooting pocket and rise immediately. The closeout is short and under control — no contest at the catch, and any extra dribble lets him recover.",
    "acceptable_reads": [
      "Rip and drive baseline if the defender is sprinting past — produces a layup or kickout, but loses the clean catch-and-shoot."
    ],
    "bad_reads": [
      "Pass back to the point — gives up the open look and resets the defense.",
      "Hold and pump fake — the defender closes the cushion and contests."
    ],
    "common_miss_reason": "Loyalty to the dribble. Wings catch and put the ball on the floor by reflex even when the defender's cushion already gives them the shot.",
    "why_best_read_works": "The defender was helping one pass away. Closing out from the help position cannot beat the ball — a catch in the shooting pocket forces the contest before his hands are up. The shot is open precisely because the defender bet on the help.",
    "decoder_teaching_point": "On the catch, read the closeout. Short and under control means his cushion is yours — shoot before his hands are up.",
    "lesson_connection": "advantage-or-reset",
    "explanation_md": "**Advantage or Reset.** Your defender was helping when the pass left. He's running while you're catching — he can't beat the ball. If the closeout is short and under control, catch and shoot. If he's flying past you, drive. If he's set with no advantage, reset. Look at his feet and his cushion at the catch.",
    "feedback": {
      "correct": "Good read. The closeout was short. You caught and shot before he could contest.",
      "partial": "A drive can work against a flying closeout. This one was under control and short — the shot was open. Take it.",
      "wrong": "Look at the closeout. If the defender is short and under control at the catch, the shot is open. Catch and shoot."
    },
    "self_review_checklist": [
